WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.240 --> 00:00:04.540
Okay, I want to start the session. So welcome, everyone.

2
00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:08.061
I'm Gadi Getz. I'm from Mass General Hospital and the Broad

3
00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:11.620
Institute, and I welcome you to this session on new insights from

4
00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:15.320
TCGA whole-genome sequencing. And since this is

5
00:00:15.420 --> 00:00:18.960
an educational session, I will start first with a kind of longer

6
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.920
introduction about TCGA, and if you are new to cancer genomics

7
00:00:23.500 --> 00:00:26.940
and the whole-genome sequencing that was done together with TCGA data.

8
00:00:27.540 --> 00:00:29.040
So here are my disclosures.

9
00:00:30.260 --> 00:00:34.070
So it's useful, when you think about cancer genomics, to think about the whole

10
00:00:34.140 --> 00:00:37.780
life history of cancer. Cancer is a disease of the genome and the epigenome.

11
00:00:38.340 --> 00:00:41.470
We all start from a single fertilized egg with

12
00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:45.070
DNA coming from mom and dad, and potentially also with

13
00:00:45.460 --> 00:00:49.269
possible germline risk alleles. As cells divide, or

14
00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:52.180
even if they don't divide, they accumulate DNA damage, and there are repair

15
00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:55.940
mechanisms in the cells that are used to repair the damage, but the

16
00:00:55.980 --> 00:00:59.000
damage that is not repaired can stay as mutations.

17
00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:03.120
Most of those mutations don't do anything. We call them passenger events.

18
00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:07.400
But occasionally, there could be an event that increases the fitness of the

19
00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:11.479
cells, and the clone starts to either grow faster or die

20
00:01:11.540 --> 00:01:13.980
slower, and it accumulates, and that clone grows.

21
00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:18.100
This is still not cancer. It occurs in every tissue in our body.

22
00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:22.220
But then it continues to divide in the clone and many more passenger

23
00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:26.000
events occur. And here's another driver event that increase further the

24
00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:29.980
fitness of the cells, and they start to take over the population of cells.

25
00:01:30.070 --> 00:01:34.010
And here's another driver. And this one is the last clonal driver,

26
00:01:34.100 --> 00:01:37.340
meaning that all the cancer cells are descendant of that cell.

27
00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:40.980
And this is very important because that means that the cancer cells

28
00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:45.320
have all the mutations that were acquired all the way back in this lineage

29
00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:48.110
from this cell all the way to the fertilized egg.

30
00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:52.140
And then cancer continues to evolve with subclones driven by

31
00:01:52.180 --> 00:01:55.760
drivers. And then when cancer is diagnosed, the DNA

32
00:01:55.840 --> 00:01:59.480
is highly altered with between

33
00:01:59.700 --> 00:02:03.040
300 and 300,000 mutations in the genome.

34
00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:06.110
The genome, just to remind people, is 3 billion bases.

35
00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:10.361
But only a handful of these mutations are actually the drivers that gave the

36
00:02:10.420 --> 00:02:13.850
cells the fitness advantage, and potentially zero or one of these

37
00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:17.260
germline risk alleles.

38
00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:21.880
After treatment, cancer continues to evolve, but since TCGA and also

39
00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:24.200
ICGC, which we'll mention, the PEACOCK project,

40
00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:28.140
worked on primary tumors, we won't focus on this today.

41
00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:30.220
Now, where are all these mutations coming from?

42
00:02:30.290 --> 00:02:33.060
They are coming from mutational processes that occur

43
00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:37.160
in different cells in the body. There are these aging

44
00:02:37.820 --> 00:02:41.730
processes like this deamination of methylated cytosine in CpGs,

45
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:43.989
and they occur in all cells in the body.

46
00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:47.790
There could be carcinogens, like cigarette smoke or UV light, that generate their

47
00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:51.500
own pattern of mutations. And also, there could be some driver events that

48
00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:55.900
create defects in DNA repair genes, and from that point on,

49
00:02:56.360 --> 00:03:00.180
the damage that would have been repaired is not

50
00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:04.080
repaired as efficiently, and you get more mutations in with their

51
00:03:04.180 --> 00:03:07.980
signatures. And of course, if the tumor is treated with the

52
00:03:08.040 --> 00:03:11.360
DNA-damaging agent, there could have also signatures or

53
00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:14.280
processes that are caused by, for example, chemotherapy.

54
00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:17.299
But again, we'll talk about primary tumors that are mostly untreated.

55
00:03:18.460 --> 00:03:22.140
So in order to study all of these aspects, and particularly these driver

56
00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:25.540
mutations, there are cancer genome projects started two

57
00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:28.880
decades ago, including TCGA. And the main

58
00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:32.640
goal is to generate a comprehensive list of genes and pathways

59
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.320
and regions of the genome that drive cancer.

60
00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:40.950
Also find molecular subtypes and study mutational processes,

61
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.940
what generates mutations, and associate all of these findings with outcome of

62
00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.829
the cancer. Of course, when I say cancer is a disease of the genome and

63
00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:52.860
epigenome, is because also epigenetic changes that are copied from mother cell

64
00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:56.080
to daughter cell also can be kind of cancer-causing.

65
00:03:57.020 --> 00:04:00.049
So this is the TCGA project, started in 2006,

66
00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:04.860
with studying three tumor types and then extended in 2009 to study

67
00:04:04.920 --> 00:04:08.360
33 tumor types, 20 kind of larger tumor types and

68
00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:12.180
13 more rare cancer types that are smaller cohorts.

69
00:04:12.490 --> 00:04:16.200
And then it's formally ended generating data in 2016

70
00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:20.800
and published a comprehensive analysis

71
00:04:20.860 --> 00:04:24.700
of all the data in 2018. Now, every tumor in

72
00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:26.860
TCGA, tumor normal pair, had

73
00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:32.540
whole exome sequencing. Roughly 10% had originally PCR

74
00:04:32.780 --> 00:04:33.240
plus

75
00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:38.620
deeper whole-genome sequencing, and 20% had low-coverage whole-genome

76
00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:42.330
sequencing, and then RNA-Seq for mRNA and microRNA, SNP arrays,

77
00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:46.100
methylation arrays, some proteomic data with reverse phase

78
00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:47.920
protein arrays, and clinical data.

79
00:04:48.920 --> 00:04:50.680
Similar projects around the world,

80
00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:55.600
combined under the umbrella of the International Cancer Genome Consortium, aim

81
00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:59.600
to study 50 tumor types, again, with the same study design of 500 tumor

82
00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:03.500
normal pairs each. So there are more recent large-scale

83
00:05:03.560 --> 00:05:07.550
projects, including kind of in Genomics England, and BC Cancer, and

84
00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:11.120
Hardwick Medical Center, and ICGC Argo, and Japan Cancer

85
00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:14.820
Sequencing, and others that are studying kind of large-scale cancer genomics.

86
00:05:16.060 --> 00:05:18.140
So what are the key tasks in cancer genomics?

87
00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:20.720
Once you start, you get these tumor normal pairs.

88
00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:25.090
The first thing is to identify all the changes that happen from normal cells

89
00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:29.060
to cancer cells, and we call this characterization, finding all these

90
00:05:29.140 --> 00:05:32.800
somatic events, including also finding the germline events, and that's per

91
00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:33.700
individual.

92
00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:38.300
Then we take all this data across a cohort of patients

93
00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:42.760
and study, and we call that phase interpretation, where we discover

94
00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:46.960
new drivers and subtypes and associate it with

95
00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:50.000
outcome and mutational processes and things like that.

96
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.840
The power for these studies

97
00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:55.560
come from

98
00:05:56.440 --> 00:06:00.090
sequencing depth of the-- in the individual, sequencing depth and quality and

99
00:06:00.580 --> 00:06:03.520
read length, and for the discovery part, the size of the

100
00:06:03.560 --> 00:06:07.260
cohort.So this is the TCGA and all tumor types in TCGA.

101
00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:11.240
Every tumor type was studied, and then at some point,

102
00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:15.000
a paper came out, we call it the marker paper, and studied some number of

103
00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:18.380
cases. And then later on, more cases were

104
00:06:19.020 --> 00:06:21.660
acquired, and that's the column of the cases of

105
00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:25.640
characterized, and overall, 11,000 cancers.

106
00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:28.600
So in 2018,

107
00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:33.460
all of the data were harmonized and processed together in this

108
00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:37.560
effort called the Pan-Can Atlas, and multiple papers were published in three

109
00:06:37.660 --> 00:06:41.560
categories. And all the mutations were processed by multiple

110
00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:45.120
centers and called this MC3 for

111
00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:47.900
multi-center mutation calling in multiple cancers.

112
00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:52.720
Then joining forces with ICGC, created this project called

113
00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:56.300
the PEACoG, Pan-Cancer Analysis of Whole Genomes, focusing on

114
00:06:56.440 --> 00:07:00.240
2,600 tumor normal pairs for whole genomes, because the

115
00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:02.940
Pan-Can Atlas focused mostly on whole exome data.

116
00:07:03.800 --> 00:07:07.580
And that also was analyzed in a large cohort of

117
00:07:08.280 --> 00:07:11.880
researchers around the world, publishing in 2020, a bunch of

118
00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:15.900
papers, a collection of papers, and here are some examples of papers

119
00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:19.780
that were published. And the main key findings of

120
00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:23.720
the PEACoG was that the cancer has on average four to five drivers.

121
00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:26.220
The majority of drivers are in coding regions.

122
00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:28.140
Third promoter mutation is an outlier.

123
00:07:28.580 --> 00:07:30.780
5% of cancers have no clear driver.

124
00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:35.220
Cancer clones initiate decades before diagnosis.

125
00:07:35.800 --> 00:07:39.540
Many cancers harbor complex genomic events like chromothripsis or

126
00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:42.780
chromoplexy or retrotransposition.

127
00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:46.760
There are different mutational processes for single-base substitutions or

128
00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:48.600
double-base substitutions and indels.

129
00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:51.780
Some of them, the etiology is known, some is unknown.

130
00:07:53.680 --> 00:07:57.390
8% of cancer have predisposition germline alleles, and

131
00:07:57.460 --> 00:08:01.440
tumor types and cell of origin could be predicted by the pattern of mutations.

132
00:08:02.540 --> 00:08:06.200
What are the limitations of PEACoG? There are four main limitations.

133
00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:10.060
One is the lower depth of sequencing with only 30 to 50X

134
00:08:10.100 --> 00:08:14.080
coverage. There are missing mutations because the PCR amplification

135
00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:16.820
of the whole genomes not

136
00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:20.780
amplifies well GC-rich regions, so

137
00:08:21.080 --> 00:08:24.700
you lose mutations. And there's, sorry, lack of power

138
00:08:24.860 --> 00:08:28.580
because the number of tumors per tumor type was relatively

139
00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:32.341
small, and some of the drivers are tumor type specific, particularly the

140
00:08:32.380 --> 00:08:36.341
regulatory ones. And not all of the PEACoG had

141
00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:39.220
other data types, as opposed to TCGA, where all these

142
00:08:40.321 --> 00:08:43.640
other data types like RNA and microRNA and proteomics, et cetera.

143
00:08:44.180 --> 00:08:47.940
So since then, TCGA

144
00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:51.760
and the NCI sequenced deeply these whole genome

145
00:08:51.820 --> 00:08:55.120
sequencing of nearly all of the TCGA cases, more than

146
00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:56.940
8,500 tumor normal pairs.

147
00:08:57.780 --> 00:09:01.260
Deep sequencing of 80X with newer technologies of

148
00:09:01.340 --> 00:09:04.860
sequencing. They are PCR-free rather than PCR

149
00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:08.860
plus, and there's all this rich and curated dataset like

150
00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:11.520
whole exome and RNA-Seq and microRNA-Seq, et cetera.

151
00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:15.280
And as you can see in this plot, the blue is the

152
00:09:15.420 --> 00:09:18.920
8,500 cases compared to the yellow, which were done in the PEACoG.

153
00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:23.510
How do you get to this data? You could go to the GDC, the Genomics Data

154
00:09:23.620 --> 00:09:27.460
Commons, and put your dbGaP credentials and select the right samples

155
00:09:27.480 --> 00:09:30.900
that you want and filter them to have the high coverage, and then you could

156
00:09:31.200 --> 00:09:33.900
download those whole genome sequencing data.

