00:13:18.060 --> 00:13:21.480
architecture, you can get these things from exomes as well, but the data

222
00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:24.160
from whole-genome tends to be a bit more robust.

223
00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:29.000
And speaking of mutational profiles, I just want to highlight the taxonomy of

224
00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:31.950
somatic mutations. I'm sure many of you have seen this before, but if you look at

225
00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:35.620
the right-hand side, these are just COSMIC-based definitions of single-base

226
00:13:35.700 --> 00:13:38.580
substitution profiles, indel, structural variant, copy number.

227
00:13:39.040 --> 00:13:42.820
So the numbers there represent the number of features, and so each mutation of

228
00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:46.420
that particular type will go into one of those slots on that histogram.

229
00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:50.350
So this is really a way of doing featurization of

230
00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:54.560
whole-genome data. So you strip away the actual coordinates of where a

231
00:13:54.600 --> 00:13:58.330
mutation occurs, and you're saying, "Well, what's the local mutation context and

232
00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:01.880
where this is actually happening?" And based on that, you end up categorizing them

233
00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.420
into one of those channels, and that's what makes up your

234
00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:09.320
profile itself. And these are really biologically informed a priori designs

235
00:14:09.400 --> 00:14:11.320
of how these profiles were constructed.

236
00:14:13.040 --> 00:14:16.990
And really the workhorse related to analyzing

237
00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.920
these profiles is something called non-negative matrix factorization.

238
00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:23.220
I'm sure, again, if you're familiar with signatures, you've heard of this.

239
00:14:23.280 --> 00:14:24.250
But really,

240
00:14:25.140 --> 00:14:28.680
non-negative matrix factorization, or NMF, was a method that was

241
00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:32.440
popularized in the late '90s in terms of just a general method, not specific

242
00:14:32.449 --> 00:14:35.620
within genomics. But it's really learning parts-based

243
00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:37.100
representation of

244
00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:40.060
particular profiles. And really it has

245
00:14:40.860 --> 00:14:44.560
this constraint where it is non-negative, meaning that it's linear and the

246
00:14:44.580 --> 00:14:46.520
parts have to be additive. And

247
00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:51.360
pretty much any application of NMF, what you're really saying is you have visible

248
00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:55.160
variables, and then you actually try to approximate them by multiplying

249
00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:57.740
hidden variables by weight. So you're trying to estimate these.

250
00:14:57.800 --> 00:15:01.640
So in the context of mutational signatures, which was pioneered by Alexandrov and

251
00:15:01.690 --> 00:15:05.300
colleagues and a bunch of folks at Sanger, Serena Nik-Sin and all as well,

252
00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:07.940
that's where you end up having your visible profiles.

253
00:15:08.320 --> 00:15:11.060
You're trying to estimate the signatures that are present in that data.

254
00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:15.140
And then also you get your W matrix, which is the activities of those signatures

255
00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:17.180
within those particular patients.

256
00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:23.180
And when we apply this to large collections of data, you can

257
00:15:23.220 --> 00:15:27.020
actually define signatures you have, just the toy example on the left-hand

258
00:15:27.060 --> 00:15:30.920
side there. And again, once you define

259
00:15:30.960 --> 00:15:33.340
these signatures robustly across...

260
00:15:34.020 --> 00:15:37.380
These days, we're talking thousands if not tens of thousands of

261
00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:41.170
genomes that are required to really be at the scale that

262
00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:43.160
some of the big players are operating.

263
00:15:43.620 --> 00:15:45.620
Once you have that, you start to look for etiologies.

264
00:15:45.700 --> 00:15:48.700
Here are two classic ones that have been around for quite a while.

265
00:15:48.780 --> 00:15:52.480
So you have SBS2, which is related to apobec base mutagenesis.

266
00:15:52.540 --> 00:15:56.520
Just giving you another example with ID3, where that's related to tobacco smoking.

267
00:15:56.920 --> 00:16:00.580
But the whole point is once you end up having these mutational signatures,

268
00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.560
you can assign them etiologies. Not all of them will have etiologies.

269
00:16:04.580 --> 00:16:05.390
We're still trying to

270
00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:10.360
understand what many of these do. But then they're often released by these large

271
00:16:10.380 --> 00:16:13.140
consortiums or larger groups who pioneer this work as catalogs.

272
00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:15.440
So here I'm just highlighting COSMIC and Signal.

273
00:16:15.920 --> 00:16:19.820
And for these, you can use these catalogs for reference

274
00:16:19.880 --> 00:16:22.180
signature assignment. So you assign it to your own data.

275
00:16:22.540 --> 00:16:25.380
Maybe it can be a comparison to signature extraction that you're doing over your

276
00:16:25.400 --> 00:16:28.100
own data as well, but also just a comprehensive

277
00:16:29.040 --> 00:16:32.260
resource for understanding mutagenesis patterns in general across many different

278
00:16:32.300 --> 00:16:33.220
mutational classes.

279
00:16:34.700 --> 00:16:34.820
So

280
00:16:36.080 --> 00:16:39.320
really this process has evolved quite a bit in terms of the timeline of mutational

281
00:16:39.339 --> 00:16:42.570
signatures. We went from 21 breast cancer genomes where

282
00:16:44.519 --> 00:16:48.450
five single-base substitution signatures were discovered, to now we're looking at

283
00:16:48.480 --> 00:16:52.380
hundreds of different signatures across many, many different mutational classes.

284
00:16:52.460 --> 00:16:56.170
And along with this, again, these tools have been developed, such as

285
00:16:56.180 --> 00:16:59.630
SigProfiler by the Alexandrov lab, signature tools led by the Nik-Sin and all

286
00:16:59.700 --> 00:17:02.880
lab. I believe Gad's group has Signature Analyzer.

287
00:17:03.260 --> 00:17:05.340
Various tools that allow different groups to then

288
00:17:06.300 --> 00:17:10.100
take these reference signatures and essentially look at the activities of these

289
00:17:10.141 --> 00:17:13.421
various signatures in their samples or even try to extract their own.

290
00:17:13.940 --> 00:17:17.540
And the point being here is that mutational signature analysis, if you're working

291
00:17:17.580 --> 00:17:21.171
with exomes or genomes, is pretty much standard these days.

292
00:17:21.460 --> 00:17:24.710
Especially if you're looking at any new cohort, you're going to be asked what

293
00:17:24.740 --> 00:17:27.360
signatures are present, are there new signatures there, et cetera.

294
00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:32.740
And this timeline is continuing. Just a couple of months ago, a paper by

295
00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:36.960
Everall and colleagues came out in "Nature Genetics" where they identified

296
00:17:37.100 --> 00:17:40.680
136 signatures where 26 of them are new, and they did a

297
00:17:40.740 --> 00:17:44.020
comprehensive analysis across the five main classes of

298
00:17:45.340 --> 00:17:46.900
mutational types that have been analyzed.

299
00:17:46.940 --> 00:17:49.260
So this was done over Genomics England data.

300
00:17:49.420 --> 00:17:51.700
So not TCGA, but Genomics England.

301
00:17:52.280 --> 00:17:56.140
They had some cool findings from there, such as the scars of exogenous

302
00:17:56.220 --> 00:17:57.050
mutational processes

303
00:17:57.900 --> 00:18:01.060
looking like they occur earlier, being more clonal events compared to

304
00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:05.820
endogenous ones. But another interesting aspect,

305
00:18:05.860 --> 00:18:09.240
and this type of analysis has been done before, but since it's Genomics England,

306
00:18:09.300 --> 00:18:12.060
they have their whole genome data that's connected to more clinical records.

307
00:18:12.100 --> 00:18:15.990
So they're able to look at signatures, associate them with overall survival, and

308
00:18:16.020 --> 00:18:19.270
then also look at therapeutic response as well, and see if they're associated with

309
00:18:19.300 --> 00:18:22.612
those signatures.So related to that,

310
00:18:22.912 --> 00:18:26.742
I just thought it'd be worth talking briefly a bit about the clinical relevance of

311
00:18:26.772 --> 00:18:27.712
mutational signatures.

312
00:18:28.772 --> 00:18:32.172
Here are just three examples, but I think these are the big ones where this comes

313
00:18:32.272 --> 00:18:35.902
up, and this is highlighting all the three different types where you can have

314
00:18:35.932 --> 00:18:39.822
signatures aid detection of a particular phenotype, and if you detect that

315
00:18:39.832 --> 00:18:43.672
phenotype, those patients are eligible for a certain treatment

316
00:18:43.992 --> 00:18:47.752
option in which it's been shown that those individuals that have that

317
00:18:47.772 --> 00:18:49.552
phenotype are likely to respond to that therapy.

318
00:18:50.112 --> 00:18:51.172
So here's one, homologous

319
00:18:52.252 --> 00:18:55.462
recombination deficiency, which will be coming up again later.

320
00:18:55.492 --> 00:18:59.032
Multiple signatures associated with it, and then you have tools like HRDetect,

321
00:18:59.052 --> 00:19:03.032
Sigma, that try to take those signatures explicitly and try to refine them in a

322
00:19:03.052 --> 00:19:06.492
way that you can actually predict cases that you think are HRD and will respond to

323
00:19:06.512 --> 00:19:10.252
therapeutics. And the same is the case for mismatch repair

324
00:19:10.272 --> 00:19:13.612
deficiency and high tumor mutational burden, where you can actually use

325
00:19:14.392 --> 00:19:17.392
signatures to try to better inform predictive tools to say, "Do you think this

326
00:19:17.412 --> 00:19:19.091
patient would respond to a therapy or not?"

327
00:19:19.972 --> 00:19:23.832
So given that background, I think here's just the slight pivot that

328
00:19:24.072 --> 00:19:27.592
I think is very important to recognize, is

329
00:19:27.632 --> 00:19:31.312
that NMF and mutational signatures themselves are absolutely

330
00:19:31.392 --> 00:19:33.832
fantastic. They've given such insights

331
00:19:34.132 --> 00:19:37.862
to so many things that we were unaware of before those methods were

332
00:19:37.892 --> 00:19:41.792
applied. But it's important to recognize that identifying the cause of

333
00:19:41.852 --> 00:19:44.372
something is different from predicting an outcome.

334
00:19:44.912 --> 00:19:48.752
So in the sense where NMF itself really excels of

335
00:19:49.112 --> 00:19:52.622
looking at understanding mutational processes and looking at a patient saying,

336
00:19:53.082 --> 00:19:56.862
"What is the likely source of these mutations that we're seeing?" It's not

337
00:19:56.912 --> 00:19:59.412
exactly optimized to do clinical predictions.

338
00:19:59.452 --> 00:20:02.772
It doesn't mean it can't be used for this, but that's not necessarily its purpose.

339
00:20:02.822 --> 00:20:05.962
Its purpose was to do the math that I've showed in the previous slide, and not

340
00:20:05.992 --> 00:20:09.062
necessarily predictions based on the activities of that matrix

341
00:20:09.092 --> 00:20:13.062
outputs. So there are other approaches that you could utilize that

342
00:20:13.092 --> 00:20:16.922
will ask, "Will a patient respond to therapy?" And again, you, of course, can

343
00:20:16.992 --> 00:20:19.362
utilize this, but I think it's worth thinking... Sorry.

344
00:20:19.432 --> 00:20:23.212
You can utilize NMF and signatures to do clinical prediction. It has been working.

345
00:20:23.232 --> 00:20:25.222
But the question is, are there other ways to do it as well?

346
00:20:26.712 --> 00:20:30.492
And this is primarily because we're constantly within the AI ML

347
00:20:30.511 --> 00:20:33.332
field, I think, and especially in biology, trying to balance

348
00:20:33.412 --> 00:20:36.372
interpretability and information loss.

349
00:20:36.412 --> 00:20:39.212
So in the context of whole genome sequencing, on the left-hand side, you have

350
00:20:39.252 --> 00:20:42.832
billions of reads, massive volume, high noise, tons of

351
00:20:42.872 --> 00:20:46.692
information there, but very hard to manage or even build a model around, right?

352
00:20:46.772 --> 00:20:50.012
A substantial compute required if you're going to try to do something like that.

353
00:20:50.032 --> 00:20:52.892
But we tend to then distill them down to variant calls so we can understand which

354
00:20:52.932 --> 00:20:55.352
mutations are occurring in patients, quite important.

355
00:20:55.732 --> 00:20:58.872
But from there, you can collapse them into the mutational profiles that we talked

356
00:20:58.892 --> 00:21:02.192
about, and from there, mutational profiles, you can get signatures.

357
00:21:02.712 --> 00:21:04.192
Or signature activities, I should say.

358
00:21:04.552 --> 00:21:08.452
And so when you're moving left to right, you are getting an increase in

359
00:21:08.512 --> 00:21:10.532
human interpretability of the data. Yeah?

360
00:21:11.012 --> 00:21:14.192
And very important for us to understand the biological underpinnings of some of the

361
00:21:14.212 --> 00:21:18.052
things that we're seeing. But it's important to recognize, as you do that same left

362
00:21:18.072 --> 00:21:21.412
to right, you're also losing information content. Yeah?

363
00:21:21.852 --> 00:21:25.772
And so it's really when you're going through this process, I look

364
00:21:25.812 --> 00:21:29.732
at each of these steps as a variant of lossy compression of the

365
00:21:29.792 --> 00:21:33.472
data, where you're slowly getting things that are distilled a bit more and more.

366
00:21:33.532 --> 00:21:36.872
We can interpret them, but you may have lost something that you can never recover

367
00:21:36.912 --> 00:21:40.652
from the very downstream data. And so I think a key question

368
00:21:40.872 --> 00:21:43.932
then is, instead of just... If I highlight that, yeah.

369
00:21:44.332 --> 00:21:48.112
Instead of looking at mutational signature activities, well, what if we step

370
00:21:48.152 --> 00:21:51.742
back? And what if we actually model the mutational profiles themselves?

371
00:21:51.792 --> 00:21:54.182
And you could even ask the same question, why not keep going back?

372
00:21:54.312 --> 00:21:57.212
And I think that will start to happen more and more actually.

373
00:21:57.252 --> 00:22:01.152
But the step that we took is why not actually model mutational profiles

374
00:22:01.252 --> 00:22:02.392
and then see

375
00:22:03.252 --> 00:22:04.992
if that can do better predictive tasks.

376
00:22:05.512 --> 00:22:06.512
And that's really

377
00:22:08.332 --> 00:22:11.732
where we come to this idea of neural representation or

378
00:22:11.772 --> 00:22:13.412
representation learning for predictive tasks.

379
00:22:13.432 --> 00:22:15.572
So on the left-hand side, I have traditional NMF.

380
00:22:15.772 --> 00:22:19.692
As I said, it's linear, it's additive, it's independent in terms

381
00:22:19.752 --> 00:22:22.032
of data views. So now I know I'll pivot a little bit.

382
00:22:22.072 --> 00:22:25.452
I've been referring to it as mutational classes, but within my group,

383
00:22:26.012 --> 00:22:28.532
we always talk about these as views of the data.

384
00:22:28.752 --> 00:22:31.612
It's a different type of mutation that just represents genome instability.

385
00:22:32.092 --> 00:22:34.292
And oftentimes these views or classes,

386
00:22:35.112 --> 00:22:37.432
usually within NMF, they are very independent.

387
00:22:37.512 --> 00:22:41.452
You don't extract signatures typically of indels and SBS

388
00:22:41.461 --> 00:22:44.612
together. So you don't look for interactions between those two data types.

389
00:22:45.332 --> 00:22:46.802
And that makes sense biologically and

390
00:22:46.832 --> 00:22:50.772
interpretation-wise, because we think mutational

391
00:22:50.782 --> 00:22:52.872
processes should be operating on a certain type of mutation.

392
00:22:53.392 --> 00:22:57.352
But I think especially with HRD, I always say it's an interesting case

393
00:22:57.392 --> 00:22:58.132
where you have

394
00:22:59.132 --> 00:23:02.442
signatures that are associated with the HRD phenotype that are across all four of

395
00:23:02.472 --> 00:23:05.412
the major classes, and even five, if you count double-base

396
00:23:05.432 --> 00:23:09.182
substitutions. So really, then if you're looking at neural

397
00:23:09.192 --> 00:23:13.012
representations, you have a situation where these types of approaches are

398
00:23:13.072 --> 00:23:15.851
non-linear. They can capture complex interactions.

399
00:23:15.912 --> 00:23:18.912
They can look for relationships across mutational profiles.

400
00:23:18.952 --> 00:23:21.672
So again, the different mutational classes or views.

401
00:23:22.292 --> 00:23:24.612
And then also they can be supervised.

402
00:23:24.652 --> 00:23:28.492
If you really are trying to do a predictive task, generalized learning is great,

403
00:23:28.612 --> 00:23:32.212
but almost everything you're doing some form of supervised learning over it at some

404
00:23:32.292 --> 00:23:32.632
point.

405
00:23:34.252 --> 00:23:35.632
So here I'm just

406
00:23:36.512 --> 00:23:40.472
highlighting the way that my lab has been looking at this problem, and

407
00:23:40.512 --> 00:23:43.872
that's doing multi-view learning over mutational profiles itself.

408
00:23:44.282 --> 00:23:47.752
And on the left-hand side was just our initial investigations of, is this method

409
00:23:47.992 --> 00:23:49.632
viable or is this thought process viable?

410
00:23:50.072 --> 00:23:53.882
So here we're showing just PEACOG data on the left-hand side, and what is

411
00:23:53.972 --> 00:23:57.272
on the top left plot there is we're showing the

412
00:23:57.332 --> 00:24:00.152
correlation between all cross view pairs.

413
00:24:00.192 --> 00:24:03.912
So all SBS features correlate with all indel features, all SBS

414
00:24:03.952 --> 00:24:06.572
features correlate with all SV features, et cetera, et cetera.

415
00:24:07.142 --> 00:24:10.992
And what we can see when you do that, you have pervasive relationships

416
00:24:11.032 --> 00:24:14.662
that are occurring. Some of these are weak correlations, but when you're talking

417
00:24:14.692 --> 00:24:18.032
about neural networks, 20% of things being correlated, that's information, and that

418
00:24:18.092 --> 00:24:19.872
information very much could be useful.

419
00:24:19.882 --> 00:24:23.252
And it's in general just saying these views are not independent of one another.

420
00:24:23.762 --> 00:24:27.252
And I should say, when you adjust this by purity, ploidy, does that make a

421
00:24:27.292 --> 00:24:29.652
difference? You still see almost the exact same pattern here.

422
00:24:29.992 --> 00:24:33.920
Yeah?And now when you look at the bottom, we ended up

423
00:24:33.960 --> 00:24:36.160
doing nonlinear clustering of this data.

424
00:24:36.580 --> 00:24:40.500
And so while I can't necessarily look at this and say, "Well, you have

425
00:24:40.560 --> 00:24:43.880
nonlinear patterns that are emerging," we can at least say that there are clearly

426
00:24:43.900 --> 00:24:47.040
complex relationships that are occurring across these views based on this

427
00:24:47.060 --> 00:24:48.260
clustering and what we're seeing here.

428
00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:51.660
So again, giving more evidence that there may be some interactions.

429
00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:56.800
So really we thought about doing this in terms of a shared representation approach

430
00:24:56.840 --> 00:24:57.830
and doing this type of learning.

431
00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:00.240
And here's just an example of us doing this.

432
00:25:00.270 --> 00:25:04.200
So this is HR Difuse, which is multi-view learning for pan-cancer HRD prediction.

433
00:25:04.240 --> 00:25:08.180
We did this across the majority, or all of PECAUG, but

434
00:25:08.220 --> 00:25:12.180
then we specifically went into TCGA using all of the old TCGA data

435
00:25:12.220 --> 00:25:15.740
that Gad mentioned, and explicitly asked which of these cases have evidence for

436
00:25:15.760 --> 00:25:19.370
being HRD, in the case of being BRCA1 or BRCA2 inactivated, and

437
00:25:19.440 --> 00:25:21.340
specifically grabbed all of those samples.

438
00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:25.060
Because for learning tasks like this, the problem is often positive data.

439
00:25:25.160 --> 00:25:27.180
There's lots of negative data out there, and usually

440
00:25:28.220 --> 00:25:29.920
from what we've seen, there's enough negative data.

441
00:25:29.980 --> 00:25:31.480
The problem is having enough positive data.

442
00:25:32.220 --> 00:25:36.180
So we did that, and when we talk about the HR Difuse model itself, here

443
00:25:36.220 --> 00:25:39.790
we have the four different views. Each of these have their own encoder,

444
00:25:40.050 --> 00:25:43.950
so each of these are encoded. Then they're actually fused by self-attention

445
00:25:43.980 --> 00:25:46.120
within this latent space that you have here.

446
00:25:46.140 --> 00:25:49.360
But we also have another training objective here where we use contrastive learning

447
00:25:49.370 --> 00:25:53.140
to actually shape these encodings in a way that once they're in the latent

448
00:25:53.220 --> 00:25:56.900
space, they're able to effectively pull like samples together and push

449
00:25:57.480 --> 00:26:01.020
non-like samples apart from one another, which we've actually found

450
00:26:01.040 --> 00:26:04.660
is quite effective in terms of this

451
00:26:04.720 --> 00:26:08.500
method. So not implying contrastive learning at the

452
00:26:08.540 --> 00:26:11.660
classification head, but doing it in terms of helping shape encodings.

453
00:26:12.290 --> 00:26:15.560
And once it gets to classification, classification will use that latent space to

454
00:26:15.600 --> 00:26:18.420
try to predict if a sample is HRD or HRP.

455
00:26:18.460 --> 00:26:21.820
And again, in this case, HRD are BRCA1, BRCA2 inactivation.

456
00:26:23.560 --> 00:26:26.640
And here I'm just showing the benchmarking just straight into it.

457
00:26:26.760 --> 00:26:28.480
So we had to compare this to

458
00:26:29.720 --> 00:26:32.680
two premier tools that do HRD prediction.

459
00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:36.180
One is Cord, which is a random forest-based classifier.

460
00:26:36.220 --> 00:26:40.060
The other is HRDetect, which uses lasso regression and actually featurizes

461
00:26:40.100 --> 00:26:41.800
based on mutational signatures themselves.

462
00:26:42.380 --> 00:26:46.080
And when you look at both the AUROC and the AUPRC, you see that HR

463
00:26:46.120 --> 00:26:49.700
Difuse does perform better than both these models by a fair margin.

464
00:26:49.840 --> 00:26:53.700
You compare to pure NMF, that approach actually struggles quite a bit,

465
00:26:54.160 --> 00:26:57.219
making the point that I was saying earlier of not all tools are good at

466
00:26:57.280 --> 00:27:01.240
everything. But also, and I think this is going to become more

467
00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:04.660
and more critical as people keep throwing AI models out there,

468
00:27:05.240 --> 00:27:08.520
is that we retrain Cord and HRDetect on our same exact data.

469
00:27:08.980 --> 00:27:12.670
And what we saw when we did that is they still cannot perform as well as HR Difuse.

470
00:27:12.800 --> 00:27:16.550
But this is going to start to be critical because you have this question of are

471
00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:19.960
performance gains you're getting, is it due to your data set being different, or is

472
00:27:19.980 --> 00:27:21.160
it due to your method being better?

473
00:27:21.620 --> 00:27:25.420
So I would highly encourage folks to especially test this early with your

474
00:27:25.460 --> 00:27:29.060
model to see how it's doing, if all other comparable

475
00:27:29.120 --> 00:27:31.780
approaches are doing with your own data.

476
00:27:33.270 --> 00:27:36.480
And when we look at inactivation type, we see some interesting things as well.

477
00:27:36.820 --> 00:27:40.400
Essentially, where you start to see performance differences across the three tools

478
00:27:40.480 --> 00:27:42.880
are when you look at more somatic inactivation.

479
00:27:42.920 --> 00:27:45.510
So these are things that don't involve germline

480
00:27:45.520 --> 00:27:49.200
predisposition allele at all. It's purely somatic

481
00:27:49.210 --> 00:27:52.909
mutations, could be homozygous deletion, could be somatic mutation that is

482
00:27:53.260 --> 00:27:56.330
expected to be pathogenic, non-pathogenic plus LOH, but then

483
00:27:56.420 --> 00:28:00.390
also methylation. And again, some interesting patterns

484
00:28:00.420 --> 00:28:03.800
emerging. When you look at BRCA-associated cancers, all three tools do

485
00:28:04.300 --> 00:28:07.760
relatively okay here. This might have something to do with the germline

486
00:28:07.820 --> 00:28:09.880
predisposition pattern that you're seeing here as well.

487
00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:14.040
But when you look at non-BRCA associated cancers, so breast, ovary,

488
00:28:14.140 --> 00:28:17.660
pancreas, prostate, you end up seeing a big performance difference here.

489
00:28:18.340 --> 00:28:22.300
And again, when we actually retrain, there are interesting patterns

490
00:28:22.320 --> 00:28:26.249
that we see as well, where Cord actually does a bit better when it retrains on our

491
00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:29.700
data, indicating that it could learn from that, but still not as well as HR Difuse.

492
00:28:30.160 --> 00:28:33.920
But when we train HRDetect itself, there really is no improvement that we

493
00:28:33.960 --> 00:28:37.740
saw there, indicating that featurization might actually just be really good for

494
00:28:37.800 --> 00:28:41.749
BRCA-associated cancers, and not maybe more complex non-BRCA associated

495
00:28:41.820 --> 00:28:42.280
cancers.

496
00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:48.120
And we had to come and try to ask why, and I'll try to get through this part real

497
00:28:48.159 --> 00:28:52.120
quick. We think it has quite a bit to do with micromality deletions, and the fact

498
00:28:52.159 --> 00:28:55.860
that not all cases have this canonical scar of HRD, these high

499
00:28:55.880 --> 00:28:58.500
micromality deletion proportions, and that's being indicated there.

500
00:28:59.460 --> 00:29:02.000
But we think LOO affects about 23% of cases.

501
00:29:02.420 --> 00:29:06.040
We took extreme care our second time about doing this to make sure that we are

502
00:29:06.080 --> 00:29:09.600
actually calling cases that HRD in a very rigorous way, only

503
00:29:09.640 --> 00:29:13.300
pathogenic, non-pathogenic mutations, allele-based homozygous

504
00:29:13.340 --> 00:29:16.620
deletion calls, making sure everything's standard to the community, just to make

505
00:29:16.660 --> 00:29:20.609
sure that there aren't other explanations of why these might have low micromality

506
00:29:20.620 --> 00:29:23.140
deletions. But the interesting thing too is that these

507
00:29:24.180 --> 00:29:27.460
LOO cases are in risk for other BRCA-ness patterns as well.

508
00:29:27.840 --> 00:29:31.540
So giving this intermediate phenotype between high micromality

509
00:29:31.560 --> 00:29:33.520
deletion cases and HRPs.

510
00:29:35.360 --> 00:29:39.180
And here's just showing that it's key because HRDetect and Cord

511
00:29:39.400 --> 00:29:43.140
micromality deletions are the primary feature that they use within their models to

512
00:29:43.200 --> 00:29:47.100
predict HRD. And you can see here all the tools typically do well with high, but

513
00:29:47.140 --> 00:29:50.440
then only HR Difuse is able to really pick up some of the lows.

514
00:29:50.480 --> 00:29:54.000
But as you can see, still could be improvement here based on any

515
00:29:54.040 --> 00:29:57.960
tool. But then I think this is a critical part, which I'll just try to spend a

516
00:29:58.020 --> 00:30:02.010
minute and a half on, or two minutes quickly, is why is this practically important?

517
00:30:02.880 --> 00:30:06.770
And here we really leverage the new TCGA data in order to find every

518
00:30:06.800 --> 00:30:10.590
case that it has that has platinum response data, particularly cisplatin and

519
00:30:10.620 --> 00:30:14.300
carboplatin. And so we intentionally collected a group of

520
00:30:14.700 --> 00:30:18.400
cancers that are quite difficult, and that would be non-BRCA

521
00:30:18.410 --> 00:30:21.270
associated cancers. Difficult in the sense of platinum prediction

522
00:30:22.100 --> 00:30:26.070
we assumed would not be easy there, or it would at least be harder than

523
00:30:26.100 --> 00:30:27.980
your classical ovarian cases with HRD.

524
00:30:28.920 --> 00:30:32.560
And what you can see on the bottom left is this effectively micromality deletions

525
00:30:32.620 --> 00:30:36.410
alone in that cohort do not differentiate responders and

526
00:30:36.420 --> 00:30:40.260
non-responders. And because of that, you see tools like Cord and HRDetect

527
00:30:40.620 --> 00:30:43.690
not doing well in that group. And to give them credit, I don't think they were ever

528
00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:46.300
designed for this. I don't think they looked for this or tested for this, but I

529
00:30:46.340 --> 00:30:49.876
think it's still important to point out.But HRDFuse here can

530
00:30:49.976 --> 00:30:53.316
actually... This isn't a good F1 where it's at now, but we thought, "Okay, this is

531
00:30:53.336 --> 00:30:57.236
showing promise. Can we leverage the framework further?" And this is where neural

532
00:30:57.256 --> 00:31:01.056
representation learning really benefits, and that is the concept of transfer

533
00:31:01.116 --> 00:31:03.156
learning. And this is unique to HRDFuse.

534
00:31:03.216 --> 00:31:05.496
CORG and HRDTech, based on their models, can't do it.

535
00:31:06.036 --> 00:31:09.276
So the easiest explanation I could find is think of it like this.

536
00:31:09.416 --> 00:31:09.776
You are

537
00:31:10.876 --> 00:31:12.776
pre-training a model to detect cats.

538
00:31:13.276 --> 00:31:16.116
You've done that, and now that you've trained a model to detect cats, now you want

539
00:31:16.136 --> 00:31:16.236
to

540
00:31:17.236 --> 00:31:19.356
be able to detect a subset of cats, lions.

541
00:31:19.856 --> 00:31:23.616
So what you can do is you can actually freeze your feature extractor and then

542
00:31:23.656 --> 00:31:27.436
build a new classifier that says, "I want to detect lions." So the

543
00:31:27.516 --> 00:31:31.236
idea is you can learn from cat representations in order to better predict

544
00:31:31.276 --> 00:31:34.486
lions instead of training a whole new classifier on lions themselves.

545
00:31:35.076 --> 00:31:38.976
So for us, BRCA1 and BRCA2 loss is our cat, and platinum

546
00:31:38.996 --> 00:31:40.056
response is our lion.

547
00:31:41.516 --> 00:31:44.976
And here are the results when we do that, and you can see HRDFuse fine-tuned on the

548
00:31:44.996 --> 00:31:45.856
left-hand side.

549
00:31:47.136 --> 00:31:49.376
To be honest, we're a bit shocked by how well we're able to do here.

550
00:31:49.756 --> 00:31:53.016
So this is approaching 0.75 in terms of F1.

551
00:31:53.436 --> 00:31:54.536
You can see that eclipses the

552
00:31:57.136 --> 00:32:00.816
performance of all our predictive tools, including HRDFuse baseline, and

553
00:32:00.916 --> 00:32:03.476
also when we retrain directly on platinum response.

554
00:32:03.536 --> 00:32:06.536
So that's the idea of we train a model just looking for lines.

555
00:32:06.616 --> 00:32:10.516
It does not do as well as the fine-tune model, indicating learning the BRCA1,

556
00:32:10.526 --> 00:32:12.676
BRCA2 representations actually benefited the model.

557
00:32:13.176 --> 00:32:16.396
And on the right-hand side, I'm just showing how we validate that in another small

558
00:32:16.456 --> 00:32:20.276
cohort of non-BRCA associated cancers, which we found was very hard to come by, but

559
00:32:20.316 --> 00:32:23.556
we found one to at least validate on. So the last slide.

560
00:32:23.636 --> 00:32:27.576
So I think hopefully I convinced you that neural representation learning has a lot

561
00:32:27.596 --> 00:32:30.666
of promise, especially when you're trying to predict clinical phenotypes using

562
00:32:30.696 --> 00:32:33.866
genome instability patterns. And from what I showed, you can see lots of folks are

563
00:32:33.896 --> 00:32:34.676
trying to do that task.

564
00:32:35.676 --> 00:32:39.516
TCGA, it's so cool that they have this whole genome data now, especially for us,

565
00:32:39.596 --> 00:32:42.976
because I truly think it's unlocked as a modality, where now we can look at

566
00:32:43.056 --> 00:32:45.326
multimodal models that involve whole genome sequencing.

567
00:32:45.376 --> 00:32:48.786
And I don't know all the data types that things like Genomics England and Hartwick

568
00:32:48.796 --> 00:32:52.716
has, but this is, I think, going to be very unique to TCGA and what it's actually

569
00:32:52.736 --> 00:32:54.296
unlocking in terms of multimodal modeling.

570
00:32:54.636 --> 00:32:57.096
And I think doing these types of representation learning could really start

571
00:32:57.196 --> 00:33:00.856
complementing mutational signatures, where you're using parallel approaches, one

572
00:33:00.876 --> 00:33:03.736
that's really trying to look for etiologies and one that's trying to do prediction.

573
00:33:04.456 --> 00:33:07.836
So with that, I'd just like to end. Thank my lab, thank

