00:40:50.888 --> 00:40:54.208
fundamental questions, will benefit from that kind of scale.

731
00:40:54.248 --> 00:40:57.348
And I think we look for inspiration, for example, in the germline community,

732
00:40:57.428 --> 00:41:01.348
cardiovascular disease, or all kinds of common diseases where they've gotten to

733
00:41:01.388 --> 00:41:05.248
numbers like the millions, or even in targeted sequencing, very elegant

734
00:41:05.308 --> 00:41:08.688
studies revealing surprising results from MSK, for example.

735
00:41:08.708 --> 00:41:10.528
I think I saw Mike Berger in the audience,

736
00:41:12.048 --> 00:41:14.448
from looking at tens of thousands of samples.

737
00:41:14.508 --> 00:41:14.818
So I think,

738
00:41:17.308 --> 00:41:19.508
let's get down to the topic at hand.

739
00:41:19.568 --> 00:41:23.518
So one of the reasons we're interested in analyzing cancer

740
00:41:23.588 --> 00:41:26.408
whole genomes is to study something called chromosomal instability.

741
00:41:26.508 --> 00:41:27.908
What is chromosomal instability?

742
00:41:27.968 --> 00:41:30.028
Well, there's actually,

743
00:41:30.928 --> 00:41:34.628
Nature commissioned this review on that topic, and I sort of crashed the

744
00:41:34.688 --> 00:41:38.608
party, so I've gotten some of the insights from the leaders

745
00:41:38.648 --> 00:41:41.418
in the field about it. But here's a little bit how I think about it, and

746
00:41:41.428 --> 00:41:44.238
particularly what's relevant for cancer genomics.

747
00:41:44.708 --> 00:41:47.728
So when we think about cancer genomes evolving,

748
00:41:47.828 --> 00:41:51.518
we think of many defective cellular pathways that

749
00:41:51.548 --> 00:41:55.308
are sort of regulating the homostasis of the genome from

750
00:41:56.028 --> 00:41:58.648
sort of nucleotide base excision, mismatch repair,

751
00:42:00.468 --> 00:42:04.048
double-stranded break repair, and replication, and then

752
00:42:04.088 --> 00:42:07.948
mitosis and nuclear integrity and telomere end protection.

753
00:42:07.988 --> 00:42:11.908
And these are sort of processes that have much different biology and

754
00:42:11.968 --> 00:42:13.768
operate on very different

755
00:42:14.568 --> 00:42:18.288
scales. And I don't really know what the left-hand side is, but I think the

756
00:42:18.368 --> 00:42:21.468
right-hand side is more of what we think about in terms of SIN.

757
00:42:21.508 --> 00:42:25.458
And there's some really exciting concurrent sessions and later in the

758
00:42:25.488 --> 00:42:29.028
day by Sam Vakharia and others, thinking about the therapeutic

759
00:42:29.108 --> 00:42:32.248
opportunities that arise, particularly from the right-hand

760
00:42:32.368 --> 00:42:35.528
side of this diagram. Now, when we

761
00:42:36.568 --> 00:42:39.058
triangulate this with the cancer genome, we can think about

762
00:42:39.088 --> 00:42:42.848
somatic events that happen on different scales.

763
00:42:43.108 --> 00:42:46.768
Point mutations that alter single or a few nucleotides,

764
00:42:46.848 --> 00:42:50.528
rearrangements that join distant regions or segments of the genome,

765
00:42:51.008 --> 00:42:54.088
and what we call chromosomal alterations that

766
00:42:55.308 --> 00:42:59.230
affect megabases of DNA.And we have names for

767
00:42:59.320 --> 00:43:02.600
signatures, and Jason very elegantly reviewed some of the

768
00:43:03.260 --> 00:43:07.180
approaches for deconvolution these straight from data

769
00:43:08.100 --> 00:43:11.860
from SBS and indel signatures, rearrangement signatures, and more

770
00:43:11.920 --> 00:43:14.100
recently, copy number signatures.

771
00:43:14.130 --> 00:43:18.020
And the vision here is really as we move to whole-genome molecular oncology,

772
00:43:18.030 --> 00:43:21.870
that these findings can be actionable, meaning that we can

773
00:43:21.900 --> 00:43:25.540
diagnose a sort of pathology, a defective

774
00:43:26.480 --> 00:43:30.340
cellular pathway, and triangulate that with a targetable

775
00:43:30.380 --> 00:43:34.140
synthetic lethality. And that's one way that whole

776
00:43:34.200 --> 00:43:37.880
genomes, and maybe only whole genomes, will be able to inform this kind of

777
00:43:37.920 --> 00:43:39.600
approach to

778
00:43:40.460 --> 00:43:43.700
treatment. So when we think about these different

779
00:43:44.580 --> 00:43:48.420
kind of scales of variation, there's different features that we

780
00:43:48.460 --> 00:43:52.280
think about. And for SNVs, a lot of those features have been really worked out in

781
00:43:52.320 --> 00:43:56.220
terms of what we care about when diagnosing a particular SNV or indel

782
00:43:56.260 --> 00:43:59.720
mutational process, meaning we look at the immediate nucleotide context.

783
00:44:00.420 --> 00:44:04.000
For rearrangements, these processes are generally

784
00:44:04.060 --> 00:44:05.800
represented in terms of

785
00:44:06.860 --> 00:44:10.450
the orientation of each junction, whether it's an inversion or a

786
00:44:10.480 --> 00:44:14.340
translocation or a clustered rearrangement or not, and the length, the

787
00:44:14.460 --> 00:44:15.390
span that they take.

788
00:44:16.200 --> 00:44:18.420
And thinking about copy number processes,

789
00:44:21.360 --> 00:44:25.000
the sort of methods have, right now, I think still a little bit nascent, and I

790
00:44:25.040 --> 00:44:28.320
think this is where we have a lot of room to improve.

791
00:44:28.340 --> 00:44:31.270
And when I kind of subdivided these entities,

792
00:44:31.360 --> 00:44:35.200
they do exist in sort of a continuum and when we think

793
00:44:35.260 --> 00:44:39.200
about mutational processes, we may have to think about many of these scales.

794
00:44:39.280 --> 00:44:39.420
Now,

795
00:44:40.600 --> 00:44:43.700
for better or for worse, I've spent the last decade sort of with unhealthy

796
00:44:43.760 --> 00:44:44.760
obsession about the

797
00:44:45.760 --> 00:44:49.660
way that copy number and rearrangements really are two coherent

798
00:44:49.700 --> 00:44:53.060
sort of shadows of a single cancer genome

799
00:44:53.120 --> 00:44:56.180
structure. And this is a very sort of practical

800
00:44:56.220 --> 00:44:59.880
intuition, which is that there's a stoichiometry around copy

801
00:44:59.940 --> 00:45:03.240
number alterations in the genome where we have segments that

802
00:45:03.880 --> 00:45:07.120
might have two copies, might have five copies, and they're connected to other

803
00:45:07.160 --> 00:45:09.820
segments, either in the reference through this kind of gray

804
00:45:10.780 --> 00:45:14.360
edge, or through distant connections in the genome

805
00:45:14.720 --> 00:45:18.600
made through rearrangement. And there's a sort of mass balance principle

806
00:45:18.660 --> 00:45:21.480
around this, sort of like if you think about basic chemistry.

807
00:45:21.510 --> 00:45:25.460
And the way that this is framed is that every copy of

808
00:45:25.520 --> 00:45:29.320
every segment has a left and a right neighbor, or it's at a chromosome

809
00:45:29.330 --> 00:45:32.860
end. And we can leverage this actually not just a kind of neat little fact, we

810
00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:35.960
can leverage this to build better analytics.

811
00:45:35.980 --> 00:45:39.720
And part of the output of that analytics is that we not only infer the copy

812
00:45:39.760 --> 00:45:43.380
number on the segments of the genome, but also the rearrangements, the junctions

813
00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:46.780
that connect them. And I think this is a very powerful starting point for thinking

814
00:45:46.840 --> 00:45:49.540
about particularly structural chromosomal instability.

815
00:45:50.680 --> 00:45:54.460
And so we've developed a method based around this mass balance principle

816
00:45:54.540 --> 00:45:57.480
called JAVEL, and it's undergone several iterations.

817
00:45:57.540 --> 00:46:00.480
Here's the poor PhD students who, well, they

818
00:46:02.020 --> 00:46:05.740
put a lot of their time into this approach, and I

819
00:46:05.780 --> 00:46:08.600
think it's really the state-of-the-art approach

820
00:46:08.960 --> 00:46:12.520
that takes into account rearrangements and

821
00:46:13.320 --> 00:46:16.880
copy number as input and outputs what I think is a state-of-the-art

822
00:46:18.980 --> 00:46:22.740
copy number profiles. And here's some benchmarking we did both against an

823
00:46:22.800 --> 00:46:26.540
older version of JAVEL and then the sort of rest of the pack of key

824
00:46:26.580 --> 00:46:30.280
methods in the field, showing markedly sort of step change in

825
00:46:30.460 --> 00:46:33.880
precision and recall for breakpoint detection and copy number

826
00:46:34.140 --> 00:46:36.570
estimation on alleles and total copy number.

827
00:46:36.570 --> 00:46:40.040
Now, this is obviously a good starting point, but where I

828
00:46:40.080 --> 00:46:43.960
think our approach really shines is in providing this feature space that we

829
00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:47.089
can start to think about structural chromosomal instability.

830
00:46:47.170 --> 00:46:50.400
And part of this is sort of this gallery that I'm showing here of the kind of

831
00:46:50.440 --> 00:46:52.750
events that we can diagnose by

832
00:46:53.820 --> 00:46:56.170
looking at patterns in these genome graphs.

833
00:46:56.220 --> 00:46:59.820
So the output of JAVEL is a genome graph, and we analyze it using a

834
00:47:01.060 --> 00:47:04.900
sort of toolkit suite called gGenome, or for

835
00:47:05.020 --> 00:47:08.620
graph genomes. So these are the patterns of both

836
00:47:08.680 --> 00:47:11.360
simple and complex rearrangements.

837
00:47:11.380 --> 00:47:14.280
And you could see that in addition to sort of deletions,

838
00:47:14.320 --> 00:47:18.030
duplications, and these kind of simple events, many

839
00:47:18.140 --> 00:47:21.960
other patterns can emerge and we can sort of pick them off the graph as

840
00:47:22.180 --> 00:47:25.800
sort of motifs. So, for example, chromoplexy are these multi-way balanced

841
00:47:26.460 --> 00:47:29.380
rearrangements that were originally identified in prostate cancer.

842
00:47:29.760 --> 00:47:33.040
These templated insertion chains came from the, actually PCOG

843
00:47:33.860 --> 00:47:37.200
analysis that we did with Peter Campbell and Elong Li.

844
00:47:38.200 --> 00:47:41.980
And chromothripsis is this dramatic chromosome

845
00:47:42.080 --> 00:47:45.220
shattering that happens when a chromosome is trapped in a micronucleus and then

846
00:47:45.240 --> 00:47:48.300
within the next cell cycle or two gets reassembled.

847
00:47:48.900 --> 00:47:52.260
Extrachromosomal DNA, there's a lot of interest in this field,

848
00:47:53.920 --> 00:47:57.400
are these circles that can amplify and become very unstable,

849
00:47:58.300 --> 00:48:01.920
and often, usually carry some

850
00:48:01.960 --> 00:48:04.720
critical classic kind of oncogene.

851
00:48:04.760 --> 00:48:08.320
And these other patterns like breakage-fusion-bridge cycles that I'll discuss in a

852
00:48:08.360 --> 00:48:08.740
little bit.

853
00:48:09.580 --> 00:48:11.720
So how did we discover these different patterns?

854
00:48:11.740 --> 00:48:15.700
Here's one called rhigma, which is a chasm of nested deletions that we

855
00:48:15.760 --> 00:48:19.560
analyzed in a previous-- This came out of a previous sort of study of

856
00:48:20.280 --> 00:48:22.460
a few thousand, a couple of thousand cancer genomes,

857
00:48:23.460 --> 00:48:26.760
where we found this clustered rearrangement pattern that wasn't chromothripsis.

858
00:48:26.800 --> 00:48:30.380
It was a cluster of nested deletions with this kind of

859
00:48:32.120 --> 00:48:35.810
stepwise drop in copy number. We called it rhigma, which means chasm in

860
00:48:35.860 --> 00:48:39.240
Greek. These rhigma, we could tell that they're a distinct

861
00:48:39.280 --> 00:48:43.080
biological entity. One thing was that these rhigma

862
00:48:43.200 --> 00:48:47.160
occurred predominantly in late replicating regions of the genome.

863
00:48:47.560 --> 00:48:50.580
They were also present in very large genes and

864
00:48:50.820 --> 00:48:54.480
overlapped with previously annotated fragile

865
00:48:54.500 --> 00:48:56.400
sites from cell line experiments.

866
00:48:57.860 --> 00:49:01.640
So here's an example of what we think is a structural mutational

867
00:49:01.680 --> 00:49:05.670
process that has a very distinct footprint on these graphs

868
00:49:05.700 --> 00:49:09.420
that we're deriving.Another one we were just hearing a

869
00:49:09.460 --> 00:49:09.910
beautiful

870
00:49:12.020 --> 00:49:14.240
discussion about homologous recombination deficiency.

871
00:49:14.300 --> 00:49:18.240
Here was a new structural scar of BRCA1 deficiency

872
00:49:18.260 --> 00:49:22.160
that we recently uncovered, and it has a very simple sort of pattern

873
00:49:22.180 --> 00:49:26.030
where you have these two duplications that are here separated by 10 or

874
00:49:26.080 --> 00:49:28.700
more megabases, but often on different chromosomes.

875
00:49:28.740 --> 00:49:30.870
And they're each linked to each other

876
00:49:31.740 --> 00:49:32.980
with a rearrangement

877
00:49:34.040 --> 00:49:37.600
junction. And what's interesting is that these can adopt very diverse

878
00:49:37.660 --> 00:49:41.380
phases from copy and paste to these complex

879
00:49:41.440 --> 00:49:44.960
quasi-balanced translocations, and they're highly enriched, almost

880
00:49:45.140 --> 00:49:47.520
pathognomonic for BRCA1 deficiency.

881
00:49:48.040 --> 00:49:51.560
Almost never seen in homologous recombination, proficient

882
00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:54.260
tumors beyond one or a couple events.

883
00:49:55.200 --> 00:49:58.620
So this is an example of where a particular biallelic

884
00:50:00.460 --> 00:50:02.500
DNA repair deficiency correlates with

885
00:50:03.500 --> 00:50:06.000
the presence of these specific graph patterns.

886
00:50:06.040 --> 00:50:09.860
Now, there's been a tremendous excitement in the field about these

887
00:50:09.920 --> 00:50:13.420
extrachromosomal DNA, and more broadly about

888
00:50:15.280 --> 00:50:17.660
focal genomic amplifications. In fact, the chair of our

889
00:50:20.040 --> 00:50:22.980
conference, Paul Michiel, has been a real champion of this field, and it's really

890
00:50:23.020 --> 00:50:26.900
exciting because these focal amplifications

891
00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:30.240
are extremely dynamic. They have unique biology,

892
00:50:30.880 --> 00:50:34.620
and are potentially a mechanism of drug resistance and potentially

893
00:50:34.700 --> 00:50:36.140
also a targetable

894
00:50:37.040 --> 00:50:40.720
therapeutic opportunity. But many alterations in

895
00:50:41.380 --> 00:50:43.720
cancer genomes, focal amplifications,

896
00:50:45.280 --> 00:50:47.120
are chromosomally integrated.

897
00:50:47.920 --> 00:50:50.780
And the classic kind of cytogenetic name for these is

898
00:50:51.920 --> 00:50:54.700
homogenous staining regions. This is what they look like sort of under the

899
00:50:54.740 --> 00:50:57.360
microscope to cytogeneticists decades ago.

900
00:50:58.260 --> 00:51:01.840
Unlike ecDNA, they're thought to segregate symmetrically and they're stable.

901
00:51:03.200 --> 00:51:07.100
And we can sort of detect very distinct footprints of these

902
00:51:07.200 --> 00:51:09.280
in our genome graphs, as I

903
00:51:10.220 --> 00:51:12.800
showed you that dictionary above.

904
00:51:12.840 --> 00:51:16.080
So applying our approaches to thousands of

905
00:51:16.260 --> 00:51:16.900
TCGA

906
00:51:18.120 --> 00:51:21.840
genomes, we developed a landscape of how

907
00:51:21.960 --> 00:51:23.800
frequent each of these patterns

908
00:51:24.700 --> 00:51:28.080
are. And we have several patterns that qualify as

909
00:51:28.760 --> 00:51:30.000
HSR in our dictionary.

910
00:51:30.940 --> 00:51:34.660
And what we see is really striking, which is that

911
00:51:34.940 --> 00:51:38.720
really, a lot of amplifications in cancer genomes fall

912
00:51:38.760 --> 00:51:42.230
into this homogenously staining region pattern, with the exception

913
00:51:42.280 --> 00:51:43.880
of glioblastoma,

914
00:51:45.240 --> 00:51:45.600
where

915
00:51:46.780 --> 00:51:50.380
these tumors indeed are dominated by ecDNA

916
00:51:50.400 --> 00:51:53.990
amplifications of EGFR and PDGFRA and these kind of

917
00:51:54.020 --> 00:51:57.940
classic oncogenes. And that's a little bit distinct, different from the

918
00:51:57.980 --> 00:51:59.620
narrative in the field,

919
00:52:00.520 --> 00:52:04.400
where ecDNA or B have been sort of found in many,

920
00:52:04.480 --> 00:52:08.000
many places. And I think it's worth taking another look

921
00:52:08.120 --> 00:52:11.080
at the dynamics of ecDNA formation.

922
00:52:11.200 --> 00:52:15.080
So the key tool that you use to analyze

923
00:52:15.140 --> 00:52:17.900
ecDNA is called Amplicon Architect.

924
00:52:18.800 --> 00:52:21.020
So we did a head-to-head study of sort of

925
00:52:21.840 --> 00:52:25.380
how frequently we detect ecDNA versus Amplicon Architect.

926
00:52:25.400 --> 00:52:26.129
And you could see that

927
00:52:27.140 --> 00:52:30.700
for everything but GBM, we tend to detect it much

928
00:52:30.760 --> 00:52:33.860
less frequently. Now, is this just a technical kind of issue

929
00:52:34.540 --> 00:52:35.230
related to

930
00:52:37.820 --> 00:52:39.600
different tools making different calls?

931
00:52:39.660 --> 00:52:41.760
Well, one of the kind of key

932
00:52:43.540 --> 00:52:47.280
classes of amplifications that we uncovered several years

933
00:52:47.320 --> 00:52:47.600
ago

934
00:52:48.400 --> 00:52:52.250
didn't really fit into the description of double minute in

935
00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:56.000
this case or an ecDNA or a breakage fusion bridge cycle, which is

936
00:52:56.780 --> 00:52:58.120
a classic form of

937
00:52:59.020 --> 00:53:02.460
a chromosomally integrated amplification. We called it Typhonis.

938
00:53:02.500 --> 00:53:05.740
Typhonis had this very dramatic pattern

939
00:53:05.800 --> 00:53:06.640
of

940
00:53:08.320 --> 00:53:12.140
not just sort of a broad footprint of extremely

941
00:53:12.180 --> 00:53:16.120
high-level amplifications, but many of these fold-back inversion

942
00:53:16.460 --> 00:53:20.180
amplifications and also rearrangements that are themselves

943
00:53:20.280 --> 00:53:23.949
amplified many times and occupy many

944
00:53:23.980 --> 00:53:27.620
copy states. And we thought this was actually a very unique pattern.

945
00:53:27.699 --> 00:53:31.180
That's why we called it Typhonis from the sort of way it looked on our

946
00:53:33.860 --> 00:53:35.940
visualizations here resembling a typhoon.

947
00:53:37.170 --> 00:53:41.100
And the one that we reported there showed that these Typhonis are, in fact,

948
00:53:41.860 --> 00:53:45.750
massively amplified homogenously staining regions, and

949
00:53:45.760 --> 00:53:48.930
this is the metaphase FISH from the same cell here that's

950
00:53:48.960 --> 00:53:52.760
co-amplifying MYCN and MIB.

951
00:53:52.820 --> 00:53:56.000
And you can see that there are two chromosomes here.

952
00:53:56.050 --> 00:53:59.560
Those are chromosomes undergone a duplication where all of these

