01:21:56.516 --> 01:21:59.436
And how do we find drivers of structural variations?

1432
01:22:00.276 --> 01:22:04.236
We have multiple tools. One tool that we recently developed, which is kind of like

1433
01:22:04.276 --> 01:22:07.056
the NDS for structural variations.

1434
01:22:07.116 --> 01:22:07.796
We look at

1435
01:22:08.616 --> 01:22:12.216
structural variations that we think will have no effect, like the silent mutations

1436
01:22:12.256 --> 01:22:15.696
or the synonymous, and structural variations that we think will have an effect,

1437
01:22:16.076 --> 01:22:20.056
mostly in deleterious effect. And we look at

1438
01:22:20.096 --> 01:22:24.056
their ratio and see which ones are enriched in functional effects, and we

1439
01:22:24.096 --> 01:22:27.716
call it SVelfi. And then there's the method that we developed in

1440
01:22:27.936 --> 01:22:31.156
Ramin's lab, looking at structural variations

1441
01:22:32.516 --> 01:22:36.426
that are kind of recurrently connecting different parts of the

1442
01:22:36.516 --> 01:22:40.256
genome. So we applied these tools. I will talk about SVelfi results.

1443
01:22:41.816 --> 01:22:44.136
This, again, you could learn more in this poster here.

1444
01:22:44.556 --> 01:22:47.276
So here are the number of structural variation drivers that we found.

1445
01:22:47.336 --> 01:22:51.296
Some of them are known structural variation drivers, some are a known cancer

1446
01:22:51.356 --> 01:22:54.516
gene, and some are totally novel. Of course, some of them could be still artifacts

1447
01:22:54.556 --> 01:22:58.276
that we're looking into. Let's look at, for example, in prostate cancer that is

1448
01:22:58.296 --> 01:22:59.216
known to be affected

1449
01:23:00.076 --> 01:23:04.056
by known drivers of structural variations. So here are the top SVelfi hits.

1450
01:23:04.496 --> 01:23:07.356
The top hit is like TMPRSS2 and ERG, which we know.

1451
01:23:07.416 --> 01:23:10.376
There's PTEN and other ones, other new ones that

1452
01:23:11.196 --> 01:23:15.056
different labs are working on. But we wanted to look at this

1453
01:23:15.116 --> 01:23:15.796
one, this

1454
01:23:15.896 --> 01:23:19.676
SLC30A4 gene.

1455
01:23:20.376 --> 01:23:23.556
And this is an interesting gene. It has many translocations, both that are kind of

1456
01:23:23.636 --> 01:23:27.396
in the region, but also to other chromosomes. This is kind of what this depicts.

1457
01:23:27.456 --> 01:23:31.076
But many of them into known other cancer genes like ETV1

1458
01:23:31.116 --> 01:23:34.376
and MYC and others that are known in prostate cancer.

1459
01:23:35.516 --> 01:23:38.936
So when you look at ETV1, this kind of partner here,

